05219nam a22008895i 9781487531447DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875314477 a10.3138/97814875314472doi  a(DE-B1597)525761  a(OCoLC)1089195463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0042002bisacsh04a851/.91092231 aCannamela, Danila, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Quiet Avant‐Garde :bCrepuscular Poetry and the Twilight of Modern Humanism /cDanila Cannamela. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Poetry at the Twilight -- t1. A Matter of Things: Modernity, Modernism, Avant-Garde -- t2. The Avant-Garde Is Made of Useless Objects -- t3. Being a Living Thing: Towards a New Notion of Body -- t4. Love and the Grand Solidarity of Sound -- t5. Avant-Garde Immersive Onto-Cognition -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe blending of people and living machines is a central element in the futurist "reconstruction of the universe." However, prior to the futurist break, a group of early-twentieth-century poets, later dubbed crepuscolari (crepusculars), had already begun an attack against the dominant cultural system, using their poetry as the locus in which useless little objects clashed with the traditional poetry of human greatness and stylistic perfection. The Quiet Avant-garde draws from a number of twenty-first-century theories – vital materialism, object-oriented ontology, and environmental humanities – as well as Bruno Latour’s criticism of modernity to illustrate how the crepuscular movement sabotaged the modern mindset and launched the counter-discourse of the Italian avant-garde by blurring the line dividing people from "things." This liminal poetics, at the crossroad of tradition, modernism, and the avant-garde, acted as the initiator of the ethical and environmental transition from a universe subjected to humans to human-thing co-agency. This book proposes a contemporary reading of Italian twentieth-century movements and offers a foothold for scholars outside Italian studies to access authors who are still unexplored in North American literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zItaly. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aItalian.  aavant-garde.  acrepuscularism.  afuturism.  agender.  ahumanism.  amodernism.  anature.  anonhuman agency.  apoetics of the object.  apoetry.  asubject-object dualism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753144740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487531447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487531447.jpg  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAG